<div xmlns:oreatom="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/atom/" xmlns:ore="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/terms/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" class="item-summary-view-metadata">
<h1>Effect of sugars in solutions on subjective appetite and short-term food intake in 9- to 14-year-old normal-weight boys</h1>
<p class="author-item-view">
<a href="/xmlui/browse?value=Bellissimo, Nick&amp;type=author&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;">Bellissimo, Nick</a>
</p>
<h2>Citation</h2>Van Engelen, M., Khodabandeh, S., Akhavan, T.,  Agarwal, J.,  Gladanac, B., &amp; Bellissimo, B. (2014). Effect of sugars in solutions on subjective appetite and short-term food intake in 9- to 14-year-old normal-weight boys. European Journal of Clinical Nutrition, doi:10.1038/ejcn.2014.33Â <a href="http://www.nature.com/ejcn/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/ejcn201433a.html">(link to study)
            							</a>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Insights</h2>
<div>
<p>A high glycemic-response sugar solution suppresses food intake in children. The hypothesis that the obesity epidemic is due in part to the replacement of one type of sugar with another in foods is not supported by our study.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Practice insights</h2>
<div>
<ul>
<li>A focus on a singular nutrient as a determinant of obesity draws attention away from the real causes of obesity (i.e. decreased physical activity, increased caloric intake from many foods, and increased sedentary behaviours).</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Policy insights</h2>
<div>
<ul>
<li>Food policies for children must be predicated upon an understanding of the origins of obesity and that many factors contribute to pediatric obesity. &#13;<li />A ban on sugars may not contribute to a decline in childhood obesity.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Background/Rationale of the paper</h2>
<div>
<p>The researchers of this study wanted to understand how different sugars such as sucrose, high-fructose corn syrup (HFCS) and glucose affected appetite and food intake in adolescent boys. The researchers conducted scientific experiments in which 15 boys between 9 and 14 years of normal weight participated in four morning test sessions. The participants completed short questionnaires that tested their motivation to eat at fixed points of time during the experiment. As part of the experiment, the boys consumed a fixed quantity of a cooled sugar solution made up of various sugars sources. The participants then completed a short questionnaire where they gave the researchers feedback on how sweet or pleasant the sugar solution was. An hour after drinking each test solution, the participants ate a pizza meal until they were comfortably full.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Summary</h2>
<div>
<p>The type of sugar solution the participants consumed had an effect on the amount of pizza consumed at the next meal. The participants found glucose and sucrose solutions more pleasant in taste than the sucralose (artificial sweetener) solution, but these factors did not lead to altered food intake at the test meal.&#13;<p />Boys of healthy weight responded similarly to the effects of sucrose and HFCS.  Healthy- weight boys are able to self-regulate their food intake by decreasing calories at the next meal when offered sugars containing beverages.</p>
</div>
</div>
<h2>Contact the Ryerson researcher(s)</h2>Nick Bellissimo, Assistant Professor, School of NutritionÂ <a href="&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;mailto:nick.bellissimo@ryerson.ca">(email)
            								</a>
